              <persName xml:lang="en" corresp="#n1">M. Warkee</persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">liqa makʷās</roleName></persName>
               <persName><roleName type="title">lǝǧ</roleName></persName>
               <occupation type="political"></occupation>
               <birth when="1825"></birth>
               <floruit>He was one of the first foreign-educated Ethiopians who acted as a diplomat, secretarz and interpreter.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe received his education at the British missionary school of John Wilson in <placeName ref="LOC1956Bombay">Bombay</placeName>.
In <date>1849</date> he left India and founded a school in <placeName ref="LOC1264Adwa"></placeName> to gether with his
brother <persName ref="PRS4398GabruWa"></persName>. Later, Mǝrč̣ā Warqe became a follower of <persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros"></persName>.
He played a crucial political role during the British military compaigne led by <persName ref="PRS7484Napier"></persName>.
Mǝrč̣ā Warqe established a contact between <persName ref="PRS7484Napier"></persName> and <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"></persName>,
thus securing support for <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"></persName> after the downfall of <persName ref="PRS9430Tewodros"></persName>.
In <date>1875</date> Mǝrč̣ā Warqe was an envoy of <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"></persName> in <placeName ref="LOC2085Cairo"></placeName>.
In <date>1884</date> he acted as a secretary of <persName ref="PRS10378Yohanne"></persName>, and in <date>1896</date> he served as
an interpreter for <persName ref="PRS6668Mangasa"></persName>.
               </floruit>
               <death notBefore="1896"></death>
            </person>
